iversities and the transformation of their goals over the first half of the twentieth century from fostering moral character to promoting individualism, self-realization, and mental health.Drawing on extensive records from Canadian universities, Catherine Gidney examines the gender and class dynamics of these programs, their relationship to changes in medical and intellectual thought, and their contribution to ideas about the nature and fulfilment of the self. Her research will be of interest to historians of medicine, gender, sport, and higher education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCollege studentsxHealth and hygienezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCollege studentsxMedical carezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aUniversities and collegesxHealth promotion serviceszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aYouthxHealth and hygienezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aYouthxMedical carezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266942040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442669420423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442669420.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles